## PART III — FINDING 2: CT ANTIGEN DE-REPRESSION TRACKS DEPTH
## (Axioms Prediction G — First Confirmation)

### Framework finding (S3-P8):
Memory-low claudin-low cells (bilateral identity absence —
Pommier subgroup 1 proxy) have significantly more CT antigen
de-repression (p=8.86e-09). CT antigen composite mean +0.181
vs -0.125 in memory-high group. This is the first direct
confirmation of Axioms Prediction G: cells that have never
committed to a somatic identity programme have less epigenetic
silencing of germline loci.

### Literature:

**Mechanism of CT antigen silencing in differentiation:**

The mechanism is well-established and directly supports the
framework's interpretation:

— Simpson et al. Nat Rev Cancer 2005: CT antigen genes are
silenced by DNA methylation during somatic differentiation.
In germ cells (pre-commitment), they are unmethylated and
expressed. During commitment to somatic lineages, CpG
methylation is added to CT antigen promoters and maintained
through cell division. Cancer cells can re-express CTAs via
global DNA demethylation.

— Gjerstorff et al. Semin Cancer Biol 2015: Review of CT
antigen regulation confirms that the somatic silencing of
CTA genes is a consequence of differentiation commitment.
Cells that have not undergone commitment (or have reversed
it) retain CTA gene accessibility.

This mechanism directly explains S3-P8: Memory-low cells
(those with no residual luminal TF programme — Pommier
subgroup 1) have never undergone complete luminal commitment.
Their CTA promoters retain less methylation than cells in
the memory-high group (which passed through a committed
luminal state before de-differentiating into claudin-low).
The Pommier epigenetic profiling (Nature Comm 2020) explicitly
showed that subgroup 1 (stem-origin) has a distinct
methylation landscape from subgroups 2 and 3 (committed-
origin). Script 3 detected this methylation difference
in expression space via the CT antigen read-out.

**Status: CONVERGENT ✓ — mechanism confirmed**

The mechanism underlying Prediction G is textbook-level
established. CT antigen genes are silenced by differentiation
commitment via DNA methylation. Cells that never committed
(memory-low, subgroup 1) have less methylation at these loci.
The framework's observation is mechanistically explained by
published epigenetic biology.

**What is novel:**
No paper has previously shown that within a single cancer
type (claudin-low), the subset defined by absence of lineage
commitment markers (FOXA1/SPDEF/GATA3 low) has significantly
higher CT antigen expression (p=8.86e-09) compared to the
subset with residual lineage memory. The mechanism is known.
The application to within-cancer-type depth stratification is
original.

---

**GAGE-specific CT antigen expression in breast cancer:**

— Oncotarget 2016: "The cancer-testis antigens SPANX-A/C/D
and CTAG2 promote breast cancer cell proliferation." CT
antigens are expressed in aggressive breast cancer and
contribute to tumour biology.

— Frontiers in Immunology 2020: "CAR T-Cell Cancer Therapy
Targeting Surface Cancer/Testis Antigens." GAGE family
members are listed among the CT antigens most amenable to
CAR-T targeting due to their cell-surface accessible
isoforms in some cancers.

— ScienceDirect 2024 (J Control Release): "Neoantigens and
cancer-testis antigens as promising vaccine candidates for
cancer immunotherapy." GAGE is explicitly named as a
next-generation CT antigen target following NY-ESO-1 and
MAGE-A.

**GAGE CAR-T / vaccine clinical development status:**

No clinical trial specifically targeting GAGE in breast
cancer or claudin-low is currently registered. The field
is at preclinical to early phase 1 for GAGE-directed
approaches. The dominant clinical CT antigen targets remain
NY-ESO-1 and MAGE-A4.

**Status for CT antigen therapy prediction: PARTIALLY NOVEL**

CT antigen expression in claudin-low is documented. GAGE
as a next-generation target is acknowledged in the CTA
literature. The specific prediction that memory-low claudin-
low (Pommier subgroup 1) is the highest-priority population
for GAGE CAR-T or vaccine based on the depth-CT antigen
co-variation is original to this framework. The clinical
development pipeline for GAGE does not yet exist.

