## PART V — FINDING 4: MEMORY-LOW OS NULL (S3-P7)
## AND THE IMMUNE CANCELLATION INTERPRETATION

### Framework finding (S3-P7):
Memory-low claudin-low does NOT have worse OS than memory-
high in untreated TCGA patients (HR=1.043, p=0.878 —
genuine null, not underpowering). Interpreted as opposing
forces cancelling: CT antigen de-repression recruits immune
cells, Treg expansion suppresses them. Net effect in
untreated patients = OS equivalence. Predicted to diverge
under anti-TIGIT therapy (Treg depletion unblocks CT
antigen recognition).

### Literature:

**On genuine OS equivalence between deep and shallow
cancer subgroups in untreated patients:**

The concept that biologically distinct subgroups can have
identical outcomes in untreated cohorts is documented
in the immunotherapy era literature. Several papers have
noted that "immune-excluded" tumour subtypes (with high
immune infiltrate that is functionally suppressed) do not
show the same TIL-survival benefit as "immune-inflamed"
subtypes (where TILs are functional). The distinction
between immune infiltrate quantity and immune infiltrate
function is now standard in the breast cancer TIL field
(Denkert et al., Lancet Oncology 2018; Loi et al., 2019).

The specific prediction that a subgroup with higher CT
antigen + higher Treg creates OS equivalence to a lower-
CT-antigen / lower-Treg subgroup — and that this
equivalence would break under Treg-depleting therapy —
is not published in this form for claudin-low or any
other solid tumour type.

**Status: NOVEL ✦**

The OS null result is interpretable with established
concepts. The specific mechanistic prediction it generates
(memory-low = greatest anti-TIGIT benefit despite no OS
difference in untreated patients) is original.

