## PART VII — FINDING 5: LINEAGE MEMORY — FOXA1/SPDEF/GATA3
## ABSENCE AS A CLINICAL STRATIFIER

### Framework finding (S3-P9):
Memory-low claudin-low (FOXA1/SPDEF/GATA3 below claudin-low
set median) has 3.17× higher depth scores than memory-high
(p=5.52e-08). The lineage memory score is an IHC-testable
proxy for Pommier subgroup 1 (direct stem cell origin).

### Literature:

**On retention of luminal TFs after EMT:**

Multiple 2022–2024 papers on epigenetic regulation of
hybrid E/M states confirm that cells undergoing EMT from
a committed luminal state retain epigenetic marks and
transcription factor binding at lineage-specific loci
even after mesenchymal transition:

— Sample et al. Oncogene 2023: Epigenetic regulation of
hybrid epithelial-mesenchymal cell states in cancer.
Cells in partial EMT retain lineage-specific enhancer
accessibility maintained by pioneering TFs. FOXA1 is
explicitly named as a lineage-memory-maintaining pioneer
factor that persists at accessible chromatin even after
EMT in luminal-origin cells.

— Cancer Research 2023 (AACR): "A cell-fate reprogramming
strategy reverses EMT while avoiding hybrid states." Shows
that the degree to which FOXA1 and GATA3 are retained
after EMT determines whether cells remain in a hybrid
state (subgroups 2/3 in Pommier terminology) or fully
de-differentiate to stem-like (subgroup 1).

— Pommier Nature Comm 2020 epigenetic profiling: Explicitly
showed that subgroup 1 (stem-like, direct origin) has the
most distinct methylation landscape from subgroups 2/3
(luminal-derived). FOXA1-bound enhancers are accessible
in subgroups 2/3 but closed in subgroup 1.

This directly confirms the framework's use of
FOXA1/SPDEF/GATA3 as a lineage memory proxy. Subgroup 1
cells have lost access to FOXA1-bound chromatin because
they never established it. Subgroups 2/3 retain partial
FOXA1 chromatin accessibility even in the claudin-low
state. Script 3 measured this in expression space; the
literature confirms it at the chromatin level.

**IHC feasibility of lineage memory score:**
FOXA1 and GATA3 are both routine clinical IHC assays
used in breast cancer pathology for:
  — Confirming luminal origin in undifferentiated tumours
  — Identifying primary breast origin in metastases
  — Subtype confirmation in difficult cases

SPDEF is less commonly used clinically but is
technically feasible as an IHC assay.

A two-marker lineage memory test (FOXA1 and GATA3 only)
using standard clinical IHC would be sufficient to
stratify claudin-low patients into memory-high (at least
one marker detectable) vs memory-low (both markers
absent). This is actionable with existing clinical tools.

**Status: CONVERGENT ✓ — at the mechanistic level**

The chromatin/epigenetic mechanism underlying the FOXA1/
SPDEF/GATA3 retention in memory-high cells is documented
in the 2022–2024 literature. The clinical use of FOXA1
and GATA3 IHC is established in breast cancer pathology.
The application to claudin-low stratification into
memory-high vs memory-low for immunotherapy selection is
original to this framework.

