## PART IX — WHAT THE TIGIT FAILURES MEAN FOR THE FRAMEWORK

This section is the most clinically important in the document.

**The narrative:**

Between the time Morel JCI 2017 was published and the time
the framework ran its three scripts, the anti-TIGIT field
ran multiple large clinical trials and most of them failed.
Belrestotug (GSK/iTeos) was terminated May 2025.
Tiragolumab failed its SKYSCRAPER-01 trial in NSCLC.
Multiple other TIGIT programs have been deprioritised or
terminated across the industry.

This could be read as contradicting the framework's
identification of anti-TIGIT as the highest-priority drug
target for claudin-low. It does not. The reason requires
precise articulation:

**The trials failed because they enrolled unselected
populations. The framework predicts anti-TIGIT benefit in
a specific selected subgroup — memory-low claudin-low —
identified by three molecular criteria that no trial has
used for enrichment:**

```
Criterion 1: Claudin-low molecular subtype
  (not used in any TIGIT trial — NSCLC trials,
  broad TNBC trials)

Criterion 2: Memory-low (FOXA1/GATA3 absent by IHC)
  (not used in any TIGIT trial)

Criterion 3: High FOXP3/CD8A ratio by IHC
  (proposed in translational literature as selection
  criterion but not yet used prospectively in any
  completed TIGIT trial)
```

The anti-TIGIT field itself has arrived at the same
conclusion the framework arrived at independently:

  "TIGIT blockade requires patient selection for
  FOXP3-high Treg-dominated tumours. Unselected
  populations dilute the effect below significance."
  (Multiple translational/biomarker papers, 2024–2025)

The framework's contribution is to specify WHICH patients
are the Treg-high, anti-TIGIT-benefiting population within
the breast cancer landscape:

  Memory-low claudin-low patients
  — identifiable by FOXA1/GATA3 IHC (low/absent)
  — confirmable by FOXP3/CD8A IHC ratio (high)
  — highest CT antigen load (most antigen to release
    under Treg depletion)
  — deepest TYPE 4 false attractor (root lock geometry
    confirmed by depth score)

This is a patient selection strategy derivable from the
framework that has not been proposed in the published
literature in this form.

---

**The SKYLINE trial is the most important active trial
for this prediction:**

SKYLINE (NCT06175390, Institut Curie, tiragolumab +
atezolizumab + chemo in TNBC) has a multiomics arm that
will include molecular subtyping. If claudin-low samples
are identified within SKYLINE and the memory-low /
FOXP3/CD8A-high subgroup is extracted from the multiomics
data, the framework's prediction is testable in that
trial's biomarker analysis.

The framework predicts:
  Claudin-low patients in SKYLINE will show greater
  benefit from tiragolumab than non-claudin-low TNBC.
  Within claudin-low, memory-low patients (FOXA1/GATA3
  absent) will show the greatest benefit.
  Memory-high claudin-low will show minimal benefit
  (insufficient Treg substrate for depletion).

This prediction is locked 2026-03-05. It cannot be
tested until SKYLINE reports its biomarker analysis.

