## PART XI — WHAT THE FIELD KNOWS THAT THE FRAMEWORK DID NOT
## (Updated from BRCA-S7e)

```
FROM BRCA-S7e (carried forward):
  Anti-PD-1 monotherapy is paradoxically
  counterproductive in claudin-low (Morel JCI 2017).

NEW FROM BRCA-S7i:
  Anti-TIGIT in unselected populations also fails
  (belrestotug terminated May 2025; tiragolumab
  SKYSCRAPER-01 failed in NSCLC).

  The field consensus emerging in 2025:
  "TIGIT blockade requires patient selection for
  FOXP3-high Treg-dominated tumour microenvironments."
  This is independently convergent with the framework's
  prediction — derived from different data and different
  reasoning, arriving at the same conclusion.

  The FOXP3/CD8A ratio by IHC is validated in TNBC as
  a prognostic biomarker (BMC Cancer 2021 — METABRIC
  validated). This validation means the framework's
  primary patient selection tool is already clinically
  available and does not require novel assay development.

  FOXA1 and GATA3 IHC are already used in routine
  breast cancer pathology. The lineage memory score
  stratification can be performed using existing tests.

  Tiragolumab (ADCC-capable Fc) is mechanistically
  distinct from belrestotug (different Fc design) for
  intratumoral Treg depletion. Tiragolumab is the
  agent most aligned with the framework's mechanism
  (ADCC-mediated Treg elimination). SKYLINE is the
  correct trial to watch.
